Publicações mais recentes no YouTube

CWA Mobile Gaming
• há 2 horas
Today is the 9th anniversary of my mom's death. I don't know what compels me to share such personal stories here publicly, on my YouTube channel, especially given the nature of my normal content. I guess this snippet from a post I wrote 8 years ago explains it a bit. Tough day, today. Written in 2011: "While jogging yesterday I was thinking about my mom, Kristin Wisenor. I was thinking about one of the last things she ever said to me on this Earth. “Never hesitate to talk about me to Shaun, never be afraid to mention my name to anyone.” I thought it would be an easy promise to keep. And while every time I see Shaun I talk about my mom, I find myself feeling almost guilty talking about her in day to day life. “You can’t dwell on things, Tim.” I tell myself “You can’t put your life on hold, you must adjust Tim.” “Many people are dealing with and have dealt with loss, Tim, they don’t want to hear your hardships.” These thoughts are subconscious undertones, not things I actually believe. I must reiterate: I absolutely do not subscribe to those ideas. Society today teaches us to move on. Society pushes us to move on.. How many days does an employee generally get allotted in bereavement leave at the average work place today? The answer is, sadly, three. We generally are encouraged to get back into a routine. I’ve studied grief and learned (if you buy into it) that an average person reaches the “acceptance” phase in roughly three to five years. So why is it that society seems to deem it necessary that we return to normality in three to five weeks? I know all the cliches, “Things will never be ‘normal’ again.” “You must relearn how to live.” “You’ll never forget your loved one.” I subscribe to all these thoughts and it must be pointed out that I’m not frustrated with my personal experiences but rather the general “move on” attitude pushed upon us in modern Western culture. With these thoughts in mind I have a better understanding of the wisdom in what my mom had told me and my brothers that night. While I cannot know exactly what my mom was teaching me at the time I can only imagine the thoughts going through her head. Never be afraid to mention my name. My mother is not dead. She does not solely exist in chemical storage banks inside our minds. She did things, she changed things, she believed things, she loved…. She loved. I titled this blog entry my mom’s name. Kristin Wisenor Evans. I did this not because I planned on writing some sort of biography. I did this because I wanted to scream her name from the rooftops. I must not be afraid to talk about her. I can’t be afraid to tell people about her. Even people she had never met. Between the days of October 24th 1961 and October 22nd 2010 someone was alive in this world who had such a profound affect on myself and many others. A mother, a wife, a nurse, an advocate, an active women with passions, hobbies and loves. I wonder sometimes what happened to her hobbies? What about the books she wanted to read? What about the vacations she wanted to go on? What about seeing me and my brother get married? Grandchildren? But then I’m reminded that she’ll be there. Because she’s not gone. She’s here."
